Girls’ defending champion Topfield College retained their title at the 17th Doregos Inter-school basketball championship after a dominant performance against Roniks College. Host – Doregos Private Academy had to come from behind to beat Air Force Secondary School to win the boys’ final of the competition. From the start of the match, Topfield showed class and dexterity on the court and they showed it with their dominance display to win the encounter at 28-0 to hold on to the maiden title they won in 2020. In the boys’ final, host team Doregos repeated the quality they displayed in the semifinal against nine-time champion International School, Lagos (ISL) with a dramatic comeback against the Air Force team.   NSSF Trials: Teenage jumper Lekwot eyes Brume’s feat     NFF rolls out new qualification criteria for match…     EUROPA LEAGUE: Aribo shines in Rangers’ rout of Dortmund   Doregos were on the brink of losing the title as they were trailing their opponent 20-28 but a turn-around from the team in the last minutes of the encounter handed them the title with a 32-28 win to lift the title in front of the home fans. - Advertisement - The Most Valuable Player (MVP) award in the girls’ category was won by Topfield’s Uchechi Dike while she also ruled the three-pointer contest. Doregos’ Saka Nurudeen was adjudged the MVP for the boys’ category. In her remarks, the special guest and President of the Nigeria School Sport Federation (NSSF) Olabisi Joseph lauded the organisers for keeping faith with the tournament while pledging NSSF’s support to the tournament. “I am so excited with what I saw here today because I have been hearing about the tournament and I must commend the organisers for keeping faith and I hope we can also lend a helping hand to them to lift the fortune of the tournament. I commend the teams and I hope we can have a new set of top players emerging from the tournament,” she said. SPONSORED